title: Open Records Request regarding Daniel Holtzclaw (Oklahoma City Police Department)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Oklahoma Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Oklahoma Open Records Act, 51 O.S. § 24A.1 et seq., I respectfully request access to and copies of the following records:
All Oklahoma Open Records Act requests submitted to the City of Oklahoma City that relate in any way to former Oklahoma City police officer Daniel Holtzclaw, from January 1, 2016 through the present.

This request includes but is not limited to:
Open records requests referencing keywords “Daniel Holtzclaw” or “Officer Holtzclaw” or “Holtzclaw” by name;
Open records requests referencing case numbers 14-41539 and/or 14-49050;
Open records requests seeking records from the Oklahoma City Police Department, District Attorney’s Office, or other city agencies that pertain to the investigation, arrest, prosecution, conviction, or incarceration of Daniel Holtzclaw;
Open records requests referencing keywords “Elaine Taylor,” “Rocky Gregory,” “Kim Davis,” and/or “Valari Homan” and “Daniel Holtzclaw” or “Officer Holtzclaw” or “Holtzclaw” by name; and-
Any correspondence or documentation related to the processing and fulfilling of such Open Records Act requests.

If possible, I would appreciate the responsive records in electronic format (PDFs or similar). Please let me know in advance of any potential fees. If portions of the material are exempt under the Act, please redact those portions and provide the remainder of the records as required by law, along with a citation to the specific statutory exemption.
If you have any questions or require clarification that would assist in processing this request, I am happy to provide further information.
Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,
John Jackson

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

John Jackson

RE: PRIVACY ACT REQUEST UNDER 5 U.S.C. § 552a

Dear Sirs:

This is a request for information under the Privacy Act , 5 U.S.C. § 552a.

This Request seeks access to: a) all records and/or documents that have been prepared, received, transmitted, collected and/or maintained by the FBI, USDOJ, or DHS concerning me or my activities; b) The Terrorist Screening Database (TSDB) list for the past five (10) years; and c) the list containing all the agencies, entities, private corporations or individuals with whom you have shared the TSDB during the past five (5) years; and d) provide a copy of the Standard Nomination Form or original information that was used to place my name on the TSDB.

The undersigned also requests that you remove my name and any aliases from any  and all “Watchlists” under your agency's control. Should there be a specific procedure to go about the removal of my name from all of the Watchlists, the undersigned requests that you produce the forms, regulations, and procedures associated to such request.

The undersigned does not waive my right to appeal any objection to the production of documents listed above under (b) and (c), but agrees to obtain for the time being the page in each of the lists where her name or variations thereof appear. In consideration of the undersigned's compelling interest and need to stop the illegal targeting, derived from inclusion on the TSDB.

When carrying out the search, please do so under all of these names and aliases:

Janet Jo Przewlocki
Janet Jo Johnson
Janet Jo Westermeyer


To facilitate your search, please note that my social security number is: 083-52-1910. Date of birth is 08/08/1964. Place of birth is Des Moines, IA

The term “records” and “documents” entails copies thereof regardless of form or format and thus can be interchangeably used to include documents in paper, digital, microfilmed or electronic format; photographs, lists, flowcharts, reports, correspondence, complaints, memoranda, presentations, advisories, emails, or any other tangible form containing information relating to the undersigned in any of the name forms set for the above.

Pursuant to 522(a)(1)(D) items (b) and (c) of the documents requested above should be readily produced in as much as they have been requested by the general public more than three times.

Where a document contains information that falls into one or more of the categories described above, I seek the entirety of that document. Please disclose all segregable portions of otherwise exempt records. See 5 U.S.C. § 552(b).

Since the agency has a duty to make a reasonable effort to search for records in electronic form, I request that responsive electronic records be provided electronically in their native file format. See 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(3)(B). Alternatively, I request that the records be provided electronically in a text-searchable, static-image format (PDF), in the best image quality in the agency’s possession, and in separate, Bates-stamped files.

Should you refuse to produce a record under a statutory privilege or exemption, I ask that you list and describe the document omitted and set forth with specificity the grounds for exempting its production.

In light of the fact that the undersigned has never been accused or convicted of any crimes, if the reason for failing to produce any of the documents and/or information requested herein lies on a pending alleged investigation, you must certify that (a) the statute of limitations for the alleged crime(s) being investigated has not elapsed and (b) that the “ongoing investigation” meets the required standard of “particularized derogatory information and/or a reasonable suspicion” that the undersigned is a “a known or suspected terrorist ('KST')” required to be included in the TSDB.

In tandem with the legal provision that requires your reply to this request within 20 days, I have a compelling need that justifies that you carry out an expedited processing of this request pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(E). Namely, the urgent need to stop the illegal targeting, resulting from inclusion on the TSDB.

The undersigned expects a determination regarding expedited processing within ten calendar days. See 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(E)(ii)(I); 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(4).

If the cost of the production of the records sought herein exceeds $50.00, I request you first request my authorization.
I ask that to the extent possible, all replies, correspondence, documents and media be forwarded by means of email.
Please send all correspondence and records relating to this request to email.

If the documents or records cannot be sent by email, you should send them to the mailing address above.
​
In support for my request for expedited processing and pursuant to 28 U.S.C. § 1746, I declare under penalty of perjury that the foregoing information provided is true and correct to the best of my knowledge and belief.

Sincerely,

Janet Jo Przewlocki
/

I

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Illinois Department of Financial and Professional Regulation
Freedom of Information Act Request
Date: 5-27-25
To: Kathleen Anderson, FOIA Officer
From: Vig Sinclair
RE: FOIA Request - Illinois Professionals Health Program Records

Dear Ms. Anderson,
Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (5 ILCS 140/1 et seq.), I hereby request the following records maintained by the Illinois Department of Financial and Professional Regulation:
SPECIFIC RECORDS REQUESTED
1. Communications and Correspondence
All documents, records, communications, correspondence, emails, memoranda, letters, text messages, instant messages, and electronic communications of any kind between any IDFPR employee, contractor, or agent and any representative, employee, or agent of the Illinois Professionals Health Program (IPHP) from January 1, 2019 to the date of this request.
2. Agreements and Contracts
All contracts, agreements, memoranda of understanding, service agreements, referral agreements, formal arrangements, informal arrangements, and documents establishing any relationship between IDFPR and IPHP from January 1, 2019 to present.
3. IPHP-Related Documentation
All documents, records, files, reports, studies, evaluations, assessments, policies, procedures, guidelines, protocols, and materials of any kind that contain any reference to, mention of, or discussion of the Illinois Professionals Health Program, IPHP, physician health programs, physician monitoring programs, or impaired physician programs from January 1, 2019 to present.
4. Meeting Records
All meeting minutes, agendas, notes, recordings, transcripts, and records from any meeting, conference call, or discussion where IPHP, physician health programs, physician monitoring, or impaired physicians were discussed from January 1, 2019 to present.
5. Digital Communications Search
All electronic records, regardless of format or storage location, containing any of the following terms in the subject line, title, filename, or content:

"Illinois Professionals Health Program"
"IPHP"
"physician health"
"physician monitoring"
"impaired physician"
"substance abuse monitoring"
"behavioral health monitoring"

FORMAT AND SCOPE CLARIFICATIONS
Format: I request all responsive records in their native electronic format. For emails, please include all metadata, attachments, and embedded images.
Time Period: January 1, 2019 through the date of processing this request.
Fee Agreement: I agree to pay all reasonable copying and processing fees. Given that government records are increasingly maintained in digital format, I expect processing costs to be minimal as no physical copying should be required.
Burden Mitigation: To minimize any claimed administrative burden:

I do not require redaction of exempt information; you may produce records with exempt portions clearly marked
I do not require organization or categorization of responsive records
I accept production on a rolling basis as records are located
Electronic delivery is preferred to minimize processing time and costs

LEGAL NOTES
Clarification on Request Nature: This request seeks existing records and documents only, regardless of their internal titles, filing designations, or naming conventions. I am not requesting answers to questions or asking IDFPR to provide explanations, analyses, or opinions. Per Kenyon v. Garrels, 184 Ill. App. 3d 28 (1989), I am requesting inspection and copying of existing public records, not interrogatory-style responses. The records sought are whatever documents exist in your possession relating to the specified topics, regardless of what they may be titled or how they are categorized in your filing systems.
No Record Creation Required: This request seeks existing records only and does not ask IDFPR to create, compile, or analyze any information. The request uses standard FOIA terminology and seeks clearly identifiable categories of records that any regulatory agency would reasonably maintain regarding entities it oversees or works with.
The requested records relate to matters of significant public interest regarding physician oversight and patient safety. Transparency in regulatory relationships serves the public interest in understanding how physician monitoring is conducted in Illinois.

RESPONSE TIMELINE
Please respond within the statutory timeframe. If you need additional time to locate responsive records, please provide a written estimate of when records will be available and the basis for any delay.
If you determine that any requested records are exempt from disclosure, please provide a detailed explanation citing the specific statutory exemption and explain why the exemption applies to each withheld record.
If you claim no responsive records exist, please provide a written explanation of the search methodology used and the systems/locations searched.


Delivery Preference: Electronic delivery preferred
The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.
Sincerely,
Vig Sinclair
Medical Researcher

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Obama Presidential Library: Documents related September 22nd 2010 US Embassy Tbilisi Bombing and Aftermath
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Documents, reports, briefings, e-mails, memos, handwritten or typed notes, drafts, talking points, meeting minutes, letters, cables, text messages, notes on phone conversations, audiovisual records, photographs, audio recordings, summations of investigations, CCTV video, and any other document sent to, sent by, or received by President Barack Obama 

Regarding the following topic:

A bombing outside the US Embassy Tbilisi on September 22nd 2010. 

This bombing, allegedly orchestrated by a Russian national and GRU agent named Yevgeny Borisov, resulted in news coverage in 2011 in publications such as The Atlantic magazine ("Did a Russian Terrorist Really Blow Up the US Embassy in Tbilisi?" by Joshua Foust) and The Washington Times ("Russian Agent Linked to US Embassy Blast" by Eli Lake) and New York Times ("U.S. Ties a Russian to Bombings in Georgia" by Ellen Barry and Mark Mazzetti) newspapers. The news coverage of a Russian link to the bomb plot generated public statements from Illinois Senator Mark Kirk, and according to the aforementioned N.Y. Time article, "five United States senators — the Republicans John Kyl and John McCain of Arizona, Lindsey Graham of South Carolina and Mark Steven Kirk of Illinois, and Joseph I. Lieberman, the Connecticut independent", requested a briefing from National Security Council regarding this bombing.  

Please include a search for all documentation generated in regards to the bombing, the news coverage, and the public statement from Senator Mark Kirk, and the discussions with INTERPOL regarding the suspect, Yevgeny Borisov. A request for NSC briefing materials will be filed separately.  For the time frame for this request, please begin on the day of the bombing, September 22nd 2010, and end on January 20th of 2013. 

Provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

Thank you for the Obama Library's commitment to transparency - especially in regards to the crimes of the Putin regime. 

Link to referenced NY Times article: https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/29/world/europe/29georgia.html
